$ PowerShell: format commands

{ format cmdLets

  Some interesting → Windows/PowerShell → Windows/PowerShell/language/cmdlet[cmdLets] whose verb is `format` can be determined like so:
code {
PS C:\> get-command  -verb format                 |
  → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/nomen/object/where[where-object] {
     $_.commandType -eq    'cmdLet' -and 
     $_.source      -match 'powerShell' 
  }                                       |
  → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/nomen/object/select[select-object] name

Name
----
→ Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/nomen/custom/format[Format-Custom]
→ Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/nomen/list/format[Format-List]
→ Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/nomen/table/format[Format-Table]
→ Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/nomen/wide/format[Format-Wide]
code }

  These cmdLets control which properties of an object are displayed.


  → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/nomen/table/format[`format-table`] *pivotizes* the property values of the objects while
  → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/nomen/list/format[`format-list`] *unpivotizes* them.

  → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/nomen/wide/format[`format-wide`] only shows a single property.

}
